fields.description: The Moka Pot is a stovetop coffee maker used to make espresso-like coffee. It uses boiling water to force steam through the coffee grounds, so the coffee bubbles up into the pot versus percolating down like in brewed coffeeest
fields.name: Moka Pot

fields.description: The Aeropress is an immersion brew method. Unlike a French press or toddy system, it uses finely ground coffee and a short brew time. The pressure produced from plunging further improves extraction and flavor, and is what gives the brewed coffee a strong flavor that is reminiscent of espresso.
fields.name: AeroPress

fields.description: French press coffee is known for its heavy body and robust taste; a result of the coffee grounds being immersed in hot water for the duration of the brew instead of passing through the grounds into a pot like in a traditional drip system.
fields.name: French Press

fields.description: Chemex coffee is widely considered the better choice for people who are looking for a smoother cup with less bitterness and don't mind the lack of body.
fields.name: Chemex

fields.description: Percolators brew stronger coffee by cycling boiling water, getting double brewed coffee on the first go.
fields.name: Percolator

fields.description: The Kalita Wave dripper is one of our favorite hand brewing methods. The flat bottom provides a uniform extraction of the coffee and a delicate, aromatic cup.
fields.name: Kalita Wave

fields.description: The Hario V60 is so named because it is V-shaped, and the sides are angled at 60 degrees. There are several distinct ridges in the interior, and that, combined with the angled walls, is what helps to ensure that there is a steady, even flow of water and air over the coffee grounds.
fields.name: Hario V60

fields.description: Cold brew is simply coffee that has been brewed with cold rather than hot water and usually involves a long steeping processâ€”anywhere between 12-24 hours. In terms of flavor, cold brew is generally characterized as smooth, low-acid, and heavier than its hot brewed counterparts.
fields.name: Cold Brew

fields.description: Known for the convenience, electric filter method boil and brew your coffee for you.
fields.name: Electric Filter

fields.description: Turkish coffee is prepared in an ibrik/cezve that originated in Middle East. It's made by combining finely ground coffee beans with water (and often sugar) and bringing the liquid to a frothy foaming stage, just below boiling.
fields.name: Turkish Coffee
